\f0 Data accessibility and sharing is a huge part of digital projects. Determining who has access to information can be difficult and recent changes in legislation such as the introduction of the GDPR (General Data Protection Regulations) has changed this further recently. GDPR was introduced on May 25th 2018 ({{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.wired.co.uk/article/what-is-gdpr-uk-eu-legislation-compliance-summary-fines-2018 }}{\fldrslt{https://www.wired.co.uk/article/what-is-gdpr-uk-eu-legislation-compliance-summary-fines-2018\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs24 ) and sought to modernise previous laws on data storage and access. Essentially these regulations were brought about it order to make it easier for people to access the data that is stored about them, and to ensure that those who collect the data outline exactly what they are collecting from customers. There are, now, usually very specific checks asking whether the customer would allow their data to be stored and used.\line The point of this is to increase transparency in the whole process and formalise the data flow process more. On the whole it makes it more difficult for businesses to collect data as there are more barriers and it makes it easier for customers to decide and see how their data is being used and manipulated.\par
