1.6 Describing access issues that need taking into account - describe issues that\par
people with disabilities may face when using webpages and how we can overcome\par
them\f1\fs32\par
{\f0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://www.w3.org/WAI/EO/Drafts/WAI-access-profiles }}{\fldrslt{https://www.w3.org/WAI/EO/Drafts/WAI-access-profiles\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs32\par
\fs24 There are a variety of disabilities that can impact a persons ability to access and interpret the contents of webpages. These disabilities can be divided into visual, hearing, physical and cognitive and neurological disabilities.\par
Visual - This primarily affects the ability to see and interpret what is shown on screen. All facets of vision could be affected, including blurring of text, having a narrow field of view (i.e. tunnel vision), being able to see certain colours with colour deficiency (I am personally deuteranopic).  visual impairments can be adapted to on a simple scale by using easy to read fonts in a decent size and colourblind friendly pallettes. For more severe impairments, screen magnifiers, screen readers and text-to-speech software can be used.\par
Hearing - People may well be unable to hear the contents of videos and other audio output on a website. Having subtitles for all audio content on the site helps with this. Converting speech to text is essential.\par
Physical - These kinds of disabilities may impair a person's ability to type and use a mouse, and therefore to navigate a website. This may also stretch to voice interaction which may be a part of some webpages. This can partly be remedied by making websites compatiable with different pieces of hardware such as keyboards and different mice.\par
Cognitive and neurological disabilities - This includes a whole spectrum of impairments. On the whole these disabilities affect the ability to understand, remember and retain information. This can be remedied by having clearly organised, well laid out and well written (in some cases simply written) websites which are easily navigable.\par
